    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1975-08-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1975-08-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="104"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d104">
                <head>104. National Security Decision Memorandum 303<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d104fn1">Source: <persName corresp="#p_FGR_1">Ford</persName>
                        Library, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Institutional Files, Box 61,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSDM_1">NSDM</gloss> 303, Instructions for <gloss
                            target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> Talks in Geneva. Top Secret; Sensitive.
                        Copies were sent to the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff and the
                        Director of Central Intelligence. On August 13, <persName corresp="#p_MR_1"
                            >Molander</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SH_2"
                            >Sonnenfeldt</persName> sent <persName corresp="#p_SJR_1"
                            >Schlesinger</persName>’s comments on a draft of this <gloss
                            target="#t_NSDM_1">NSDM</gloss> to <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName>, under a covering memorandum in which they
                        explained the Secretary of Defense’s two objections. To meet <persName
                            corresp="#p_SJR_1">Schlesinger</persName>’s first objection <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> approved the recommendation to
                        “redraft the <gloss target="#t_NSDM_1">NSDM</gloss> to provide for an
                        indefinite delay in tabling the proposed ban on cruise missiles above 600
                            <gloss target="#t_km_1">km</gloss> range carried on aircraft other than
                        heavy bombers.” <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> wrote
                        “crazy” in the margin of the paragraph in which <persName corresp="#p_MR_1"
                            >Molander</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_SH_2"
                            >Sonnenfeldt</persName> stated that <persName corresp="#p_SJR_1"
                            >Schlesinger</persName> wanted to “change the cruise missile definition
                        in paragraph 2 to read ‘nuclear-armed’ rather than ‘armed.’” (Ibid.)</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1975-08-20">August 20, 1975</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list>
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                    <item>The Deputy Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Director, Arms Control and Disarmament Agency</item>
                    <item>The Chairman, <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss>
                        <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> Delegation</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Instructions for the <gloss target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> Talks in
                        Geneva</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has approved the following instructions for the Strategic Arms
                    Limitations Talks. These instructions supplement those contained in <gloss
                        target="#t_NSDM_1">NSDM</gloss> 285 and <gloss target="#t_NSDM_1"
                        >NSDM</gloss> 301.<note n="2" xml:id="d104fn2">
                        <ref target="#d93">Documents 93</ref> and <ref target="#d99"
                        >99</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>1. The Delegation should indicate to the Soviets that the <gloss target="#t_US_1"
                        >US</gloss> is willing to ban the development, testing, and deployment of
                    the following systems:</p>
                <p>—Land-based cruise missiles of intercontinental range;</p>
                <p>—Ballistic missiles capable of ranges greater than 600 <gloss target="#t_km_1"
                        >km</gloss> carried on waterborne vehicles other than submarines;</p>
                <p>—Installations for launching ballistic missiles which could be emplaced on the
                    seabed or ocean floor, including territorial seas or inland waters.</p>
                <p>2. The Delegation should propose the following definition of a cruise
                    missile:</p>
                <p>A cruise missile is any armed, unmanned, self-propelled, guided missile which
                    sustains flight through use of aerodynamic lift over most of its range.</p>
                <p>3. The following language should be substituted for the current <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> version of Article VII of the Joint Draft
                        Text:<note n="3" xml:id="d104fn3">See <ref target="#d99fn3">footnote 3,
                            Document 99</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0494" n="465" xml:id="pg_465"/>
                <p>a. The limitation provided for in Article III of this agreement shall not apply
                    to <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> and <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1"
                        >SLBM</gloss> test and training launchers.</p>
                <p>b. The parties agree that:</p>
                <p>(1) There shall be no significant increase in the number of <gloss
                        target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> or <gloss target="#t_SLBM_1">SLBM</gloss>
                    test and training launchers or in the number of such launchers for heavy
                    ICBMs.</p>
                <p>(2) Construction or conversion of <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss>
                    launchers at test ranges shall be undertaken only for purposes of testing and
                    training.</p>
                <p>(3) Operational <gloss target="#t_ICBM_1">ICBM</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_SLBM_1">SLBM</gloss> launchers used for testing or training shall
                    be considered operational launchers.</p>
                <p>In discussing the proposed language for Article VII, the Delegation should
                    indicate that it is the <gloss target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> interpretation of
                    Article VII that all operational launchers, wherever located, should be counted
                    in the 2400 aggregate. The Delegation should also state that in the <gloss
                        target="#t_US_1">US</gloss> view an increase of 15% would constitute a
                    “significant increase” within the meaning of paragraph 2a of Article VII and
                    solicit a Soviet response to this statement.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_KHA_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
